Name.creator: Rotha, Paul, $d 1907-1984
Title: Rotha (Paul) Papers, 1914-1980
Description.note: Paul Rotha (1907-1984) was a film critic, documentary filmmaker, and movie director. The collection consists of materials related to Rotha's documentary and feature films and Rotha's books on the cinema.
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.
Description.abstract: Paul Rotha was a British film critic, documentary filmmaker, producer and movie director. A former painter and designer, he became a film critic and wrote a seminal work on cinema history titled, The film till now (1930). He began making his own documentary films in association with John Grierson and was a leading figure in the British documentary movement of the 1930s and 1940s. The images in this digital collection were created in conjunction with the creation of two films: Rotha’s first documentary, Contact (1933), and Power for the Highlands (1943), a documentary produced by Rotha. Made to promote Imperial Airways and financed by Shell-Mex and BP Ltd, Contact documents air travel routes in the Middle East and Africa to show how air travel is opening up the world. Regarded as a pioneering sponsored film by many in the early documentary movement, Contact was praised for its clarity of exposition and lyrical editing. The 161 images for Contact are still photographs made during the filming in England, the Middle East, Africa and Athens. Power for the Highlands is a look at the possibilities of hydro-electric power for the Highlands of Scotland. The 71 images are movie film strips by cameraman Wolfgang Suschitzky that were intended for the creation of movie still photographs.

Name.subject: Rotha, Paul, $d 1907-1984
Title: Filmmaker Paul Rotha, camel, and local Egyptians,  Aswān, Egypt, 1933
Format.dimensions: greater than 35mm, but less than 4 x 5 inches
Description.note: “Contact" (1933) is a documentary film by Paul Rotha. Made for Imperial Airways and sponsored by Shell-Mex and BP Ltd, "Contact" shows the construction of an airplane and how air travel was opening up the world. It was filmed in England and along air routes in the Middle East, Africa and Athens. In the chapter "Making Contact 1932-33 (1973)," in A Paul Rotha Reader, Rotha writes about riding camels in Aswān in January 1933.|~|Paul Rotha, at far left of image, bent near tripod, with laden camel lying on ground, 3 native men, 1 standing, 2 seated, with desert hills in background, photographed during filming of Contact
Description.caption: Text from nitrate negative sleeve: Mr. P. Rotha, Assouan & Cairo
Description.fundingNote: Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.
